      "body": "This bug no longer operates in the way described. I have not investigated fully, but I believe that #18 fixed this bug as it is currently described. There is *still* a bug related to peer selection that exists and it is fixed by #164.\r\n\r\n**New Bug:**\r\non `master`, if you select a peer, and a peer above it disconnects or is disconnected, the selection will **slip** to the next available peer.\r\n\r\n| Select Peer  6   | Disconnect Peer 0, Peer 7 is now selected |\r\n| --------------- | ------------------------------------------ |\r\n| ![Screen Shot 2021-06-06 at 9 17 11 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/23396902/120947119-be3aed80-c70c-11eb-99e1-ad9a739df5be.png) | ![Screen Shot 2021-06-06 at 9 17 48 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/23396902/120947129-c430ce80-c70c-11eb-9c5a-8b4f32a07d7f.png) |\r\n\r\nAs shown in the screenshots above, we start by selecting `Peer 6: 149.248.3.82:38333`. `Peer 0` is then disconnected, our selection then slips to `Peer 7: 88.99.101.67:38333`.\r\n\r\n**#164 Fixes New Bug:**\r\nSo while the bug has changed, I can confirm that #164 fixes this.\r\n\r\n\r\n| Select Peer  9   | Disconnect Peer 1, Peer 6 remains Selected  |\r\n| --------------- | -------------------------------------------- |\r\n| ![pr-start](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/23396902/120947607-04448100-c70e-11eb-9794-5db5de86aea8.png) | ![pr-disconnect](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/23396902/120947622-0d355280-c70e-11eb-8379-1a5e463f0ad7.png) |\r\n\r\nThe screenshots above were taken on Linux on branch #164. We can see that we start with `Peer 9: 149.248.3.82:38333`, then we disconnect `Peer 1`. Our selection remains with `Peer 9` and does not slip.\r\n",
